RNA-Seq Training

Overview
This repository contains a subsampled RNA-seq dataset  for practicing RNA-sequencing bioinformatics workflows. 
 to execute an entire pipeline—from raw reads to differential expression—on standard laptops or training servers without requiring high-performance computing (HPC) resources.

 Experimental Design & Biological Context
The data originates from an epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition (EMT) study by *Yang et al. (2016)*.
EMT is a biological process where polarized epithelial cells undergo changes to adopt a mesenchymal cell phenotype (often associated with embryogenesis, wound healing, and cancer metastasis).

- Condition 1 (Control): Day_0 - Uninduced epithelial cells (3 Replicates)
- Condition 2 (Treatment):Day_7 - 7 days post-induction of EMT (3 Replicates)
- Sequencing Strategy: Paired-End (R1 and R2 files)

Subsampling Strategy (Why this dataset is small) -  and we need not concern with this but good to know

The original massive fastq files from the SRA database (Accession: `SRP066794`) were heavily filtered by the authors:
1. Mapped against the human reference genome.
2. Filtered to keep only reads mapping to Chromosome 18 (chr18).
3. Randomly down-sampled by an additional 50%.
4. Final Result: This dataset represents approximately 0.5% of the original sequencing depth.

File Structure
You should have 12 `fastq.gz` files in your data directory, representing 6 biological samples with Paired-End sequencing.


 data/
 ├── Day_0_1_chr18.sampled.R1.fastq.gz
 ├── Day_0_1_chr18.sampled.R2.fastq.gz
 ├── Day_0_2_chr18.sampled.R1.fastq.gz
 ├── Day_0_2_chr18.sampled.R2.fastq.gz
 ├── Day_0_3_chr18.sampled.R1.fastq.gz
 ├── Day_0_3_chr18.sampled.R2.fastq.gz
 ├── Day_7_1_chr18.sampled.R1.fastq.gz
 ├── Day_7_1_chr18.sampled.R2.fastq.gz
 ├── Day_7_2_chr18.sampled.R1.fastq.gz
 ├── Day_7_2_chr18.sampled.R2.fastq.gz
 ├── Day_7_3_chr18.sampled.R1.fastq.gz
 └── Day_7_3_chr18.sampled.R2.fastq.gz


Download the data from the follwing link - https://zenodo.org/records/7525740

Use the metadata for DeSeq2 analyses.

